== Synthesis and Meta-Analyses
<sec:trials-synthesis>

Synthesizing the ME/CFS trial literature reveals consistent patterns:
*What shows promise (moderate evidence):*
    - *Pacing/activity management*: Consistently rated most helpful by patients; supported by CPET evidence
    - *LDN*: Strong mechanistic rationale, positive patient reports, awaiting definitive RCTs
    - *CoQ10 + NADH*: Small but positive RCT evidence for fatigue reduction
    - *Rintatolimod*: Positive RCT for exercise tolerance; regulatory and access issues persist
*What has failed or shown harm:*
    - *Graded exercise therapy*: Definitive evidence of harm from patient surveys and guideline withdrawals
    - *Standard CBT* (activity-increasing variant): No objective benefit; potential for harm when it encourages envelope violation
    - *Rituximab*: Phase III RCT negative in unselected population
    - *Brief antiviral courses*: Insufficient to clear established viral reservoirs
*Critical gaps in the evidence base:*
    - No FDA- or EMA-approved treatment for ME/CFS exists
    - Most trials are underpowered (n$<$50) and use subjective outcomes
    - Biomarker-stratified trials (selecting patients by mechanism) have barely begun
    - Combination therapies addressing multiple pathophysiological mechanisms simultaneously have not been tested
    - Severe and very severe patients are systematically excluded from trials due to inability to attend research sites; the ACHTSAM pilot study @Fricke2026achtsam is the first protocol specifically designed to evaluate home-based diagnostic tolerability in patients with Bell scores $lt.eq$30
    - Two-day CPET has not been used as an outcome measure in treatment trials despite being the most objective measure of ME/CFS-specific physiology
